..TEXT:
|per non aspettar lume~: Without waiting for God's
special grace, the "light of glory," Lucifer sought to attain to
it by his own natural means.  See Thomas Aquinas, ^Summa theol.~
I, q. 63, a. 3, resp.: "Sed in hoc appetiit indebite esse similis
Deo, quia appetiit ut finem ultimum beatitudinis id ad quod
virtute suae naturae poterat pervenire, avertens suum appetitum a
beatitudine supernaturali, quae est ex gratia Dei."  ("But he
desired resemblance with God in this respect, -- by desiring, as
his last end of beatitude, something which he could attain by the
virtue of his own nature, turning his appetite away from
supernatural beatitude, which is attained by God's grace.")  On
the light of glory, which Lucifer did not wait to receive, see C.
S. Singleton (1958), pp. 20-23.  On the notion that pride
(Lucifer's sin par excellence) causes the creature to remaih
incomplete or "unripe," see n. to ^Inf.~ XIV, 48; XXV, 18.
