..TEXT:
|L@i si vedr@a, tra l'opere d'Alberto~: The adverb
|l@i~, used thrice in this device of anaphora, refers to "the
volume" (vs. 113).  With this verse begins a series of judgments
and condemnations of Christian rulers of Dante's time, their
strife held up to scorn by the poet in contrast to the ideal
unity and harmony of justice represented by the image of the
eagle.  |Alberto~: Albert of Austria, whom Dante here rebukes for
his invasion of Bohemia.  See n. to ^Purg.~ VI, 97.
